---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "../../components/PageHeader.astro";
import PresentFrame from "../../components/explore/PresentFrame.astro";
import Math from "../../components/Math.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Does the cluster survive? — Anna Rosen"
  description="Massive stars blow away the gas they formed from. Classic theory says that destroys most clusters — set the star-formation efficiency, expel the gas, and watch 10,000 real stars decide for themselves."
  path="/explore/gas-expulsion"
>
  <PageHeader eyebrow="Explore · interactive" title="Does the cluster survive?">
    <Fragment slot="lede">
      A young cluster is born inside far more gas than it turns into stars. When
      its massive stars blow that gas away, the cluster loses most of the mass
      binding it together — and the textbook calculation says it should tear
      itself apart. Set the efficiency, drain the gas, and watch 10,000 real
      stars settle the question.
    </Fragment>
  </PageHeader>

  <div class="gx wrap-wide">
    <PresentFrame
      label="A star cluster losing its natal gas"
      hint="drag to rotate · scroll to zoom · space expels the gas · R resets · F fullscreen"
    >
      <canvas slot="stage" data-cluster aria-label="A star cluster whose natal gas drains away; stars that become unbound drift outward."></canvas>
      <div slot="controls" class="gx__controls">
        <div class="gx__knobs">
          <label class="gx__knob" for="sfe">
            <span class="gx__k">
              Star-formation efficiency <Math tex={String.raw`\varepsilon`} />
              <b data-sfe-v>20%</b>
            </span>
            <input id="sfe" type="range" min="0.05" max="0.7" step="0.01" value="0.2" autocomplete="off" data-sfe />
            <span class="gx__hint">how much of the cloud became stars</span>
          </label>
          <label class="gx__knob" for="tau">
            <span class="gx__k">
              Expulsion time <Math tex={String.raw`\tau / t_\mathrm{cross}`} />
              <b data-tau-v>1.0</b>
            </span>
            <input id="tau" type="range" min="0.1" max="3" step="0.1" value="1" autocomplete="off" data-tau />
            <span class="gx__hint">below 1 is faster than the cluster can react</span>
          </label>
        </div>
        <div class="gx__actions">
          <button type="button" class="gx__go" data-go disabled>Settling…</button>
          <button type="button" class="gx__reset" data-reset>Reset</button>
        </div>
        <dl class="gx__stats">
          <div><dt>gas left</dt><dd data-gas>100%</dd></div>
          <div><dt>local <Math tex={String.raw`\varepsilon`} /></dt><dd data-local>—</dd></div>
          <div><dt>still bound</dt><dd data-surv>—</dd></div>
        </dl>
        <p class="gx__status" data-status aria-live="polite">Loading cluster…</p>
      </div>
    </PresentFrame>

    <div class="gx__note prose wrap">
      <h2>What the textbook predicts</h2>
      <p>
        If a cluster sits in virial equilibrium and you remove a fraction of its
        mass faster than it can adjust, the stars are left moving too fast for
        the shallower potential that remains. The classic estimate says a cluster
        that turned less than about a third of its cloud into stars should
        disperse entirely — which, if true, would mean almost every cluster dies
        in infancy, since observed efficiencies are far below that.
      </p>
      <p>
        Try it. Set <Math tex={String.raw`\varepsilon = 0.05`} /> and expel the
        gas as fast as the slider allows: the cluster is badly damaged, and keeps
        under half its mass. But push <Math tex={String.raw`\varepsilon`} /> to
        0.2 — still a low efficiency by the textbook standard, still supposedly
        fatal — and around 85% of the cluster survives.
      </p>

      <h2>Why it survives</h2>
      <p>
        Watch the <em>local</em> efficiency readout. It is the efficiency
        measured inside the cluster's own half-mass radius rather than across the
        whole cloud, and it is always much higher than the number you set. At a
        global <Math tex={String.raw`\varepsilon = 0.05`} /> it is about 0.44; at
        a global 0.2 it is about 0.78.
      </p>
      <p>
        That gap is the whole answer, and it comes from the model rather than
        from any assumption made here. Stars form where the gas is densest, so
        the cluster ends up sitting in the one place where nearly all the gas has
        already turned into stars. Most of the cloud's mass — the diffuse
        majority that drags the global efficiency down — is spread far outside
        the cluster and contributes almost nothing to binding it. Expelling that
        gas removes very little of what actually holds the cluster together.
      </p>

      <h2>What this is, exactly</h2>
      <p>
        The stars are the 10,000 exported from my <code>progenax</code>
        gravoturbulent model, with their real masses, positions, and turbulent
        velocities. They are integrated live in your browser, one leapfrog step
        per frame, through a spherical potential built from the cluster's own
        star distribution plus the model's own tabulated cloud profile. The gas
        dims at fixed shape because that is precisely what the integrator
        assumes — the picture and the physics are the same model.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two honest caveats. The exported initial condition is far from virial
        equilibrium and is not an equilibrium configuration of a smooth
        potential, so before any gas moves the cluster is scaled to
        <Math tex="Q = 1/2" /> and allowed to settle for 30 crossing times; the
        survival figure is measured against that settled cluster, and a run with
        no expulsion returns exactly 100%. And this is a mean-field spherical
        treatment: it captures the collective response the question turns on, and
        deliberately omits two-body relaxation and the anisotropy of real
        feedback, which my radiation-hydrodynamics work models directly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  import { loadScene, createEngine, attachInteraction, createDynamics, RELAX_TCROSS } from "../../lib/cluster";

  const canvas = document.querySelector<HTMLCanvasElement>("[data-cluster]");
  const sfeIn = document.querySelector<HTMLInputElement>("[data-sfe]");
  const tauIn = document.querySelector<HTMLInputElement>("[data-tau]");
  const goBtn = document.querySelector<HTMLButtonElement>("[data-go]");
  const resetBtn = document.querySelector<HTMLButtonElement>("[data-reset]");
  const sfeV = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-sfe-v]");
  const tauV = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-tau-v]");
  const gasV = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-gas]");
  const localV = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-local]");
  const survV = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-surv]");
  const status = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>("[data-status]");
  const frame = canvas?.closest<HTMLElement>("[data-present]");

  /** Crossing times to integrate after expulsion before calling the verdict. */
  const RUN_TCROSS = 40;
  const pct = (x: number) => `${Math.round(x * 100)}%`;

  (async () => {
    if (!canvas || !sfeIn || !tauIn || !goBtn || !resetBtn) return;
    try {
      const base = "/data/gravoturb";
      const [scene, meta, velBuf, mencBuf] = await Promise.all([
        loadScene(),
        fetch(`${base}/meta.json`).then((r) => r.json()),
        fetch(`${base}/velocities.f32`).then((r) => r.arrayBuffer()),
        fetch(`${base}/gas_menc.f32`).then((r) => r.arrayBuffer()),
      ]);

      const engine = createEngine(canvas, scene, { autoExpel: false, emphasizeHot: true });
      attachInteraction(canvas, engine);
      const dyn = createDynamics({
        stars: scene.stars,
        velocities: new Float32Array(velBuf),
        gasMenc: new Float32Array(mencBuf),
        gasMencRMax: meta.gas_menc_r_max_pc,
        G: meta.G_pc3_msun_myr2,
      });

      const mGas0 = () => dyn.mStar * (1 - dyn.getParams().sfe) / dyn.getParams().sfe;
      let armed = false; // has the settled cluster been handed to the user yet

      const apply = () => {
        dyn.setParams({ sfe: +sfeIn.value, tauOverTCross: +tauIn.value, qTarget: 0.5 });
        armed = false;
        goBtn.disabled = true;
        goBtn.textContent = "Settling…";
        if (sfeV) sfeV.textContent = pct(+sfeIn.value);
        if (tauV) tauV.textContent = (+tauIn.value).toFixed(1);
        if (survV) survV.textContent = "—";
        if (localV) localV.textContent = "—";
        engine.setGasFraction(1);
      };

      sfeIn.addEventListener("input", apply);
      tauIn.addEventListener("input", apply);
      resetBtn.addEventListener("click", apply);
      goBtn.addEventListener("click", () => dyn.beginExpulsion());

      // Present-mode keys (routed by PresentFrame).
      frame?.addEventListener("present:toggleplay", () => { if (armed) dyn.beginExpulsion(); });
      frame?.addEventListener("present:reset", apply);

      apply();

      /* One dynamics step per animation frame. dt = t_cross/8 measured at ~7.6 ms
         for 10,000 stars, which leaves room for the raymarch in a 60 Hz budget.
         diagnostics() costs ~1.8 ms, so it runs a few times a second, not every
         frame. The engine draws on its own loop and picks up the new positions. */
      let lastDiag = 0;
      const tick = (now: number) => {
        const g0 = dyn.diagnostics();
        const done = g0.phase === "expelling" && g0.tSinceExpulsion > RUN_TCROSS * dyn.tCross;
        /* Hold still once settled, until the reader presses expel. The bound
           population is already stationary, but r_h keeps oscillating, and
           expelling at a compressed rather than an expanded phase changes the
           outcome by up to ~8% — which would make the verdict depend on how
           fast the reader clicked. Pausing makes every run reproducible. */
        const holding = g0.phase === "settled";
        if (!done && !holding) {
          dyn.step(dyn.tCross / 8);
          engine.setStarPositions(dyn.positions);
        }
        if (now - lastDiag > 120) {
          lastDiag = now;
          const g = dyn.diagnostics();
          engine.setGasFraction(g.mGas / mGas0());
          if (gasV) gasV.textContent = pct(g.mGas / mGas0());
          if (g.phase === "settling") {
            if (status) status.textContent = `settling into equilibrium — ${pct(g.settleProgress)}`;
          } else if (!armed) {
            armed = true;
            goBtn.disabled = false;
            goBtn.textContent = "Expel the gas";
            /* Show the local efficiency BEFORE expelling. It is a property of the
               settled cluster, and seeing how far above the global slider it
               already sits is the point the run then confirms. */
            if (localV) localV.textContent = g.localSfe.toFixed(2);
            if (status) {
              status.textContent =
                `settled · local ε = ${g.localSfe.toFixed(2)} vs global ${pct(dyn.getParams().sfe)} · press to expel`;
            }
          }
          if (g.phase === "expelling") {
            goBtn.disabled = true;
            goBtn.textContent = "Expelling…";
            if (localV) localV.textContent = g.localSfe.toFixed(2);
            if (survV) survV.textContent = pct(g.survivingFraction);
            if (status) {
              status.textContent = done
                ? `verdict after ${RUN_TCROSS} crossing times: ${pct(g.survivingFraction)} of the cluster is still bound`
                : `expelling · t = ${g.tSinceExpulsion.toFixed(2)} Myr`;
            }
            if (done) goBtn.textContent = "Done";
          }
        }
        requestAnimationFrame(tick);
      };
      requestAnimationFrame(tick);
    } catch (err) {
      if (status) status.textContent = `Failed to load: ${String(err)}`;
    }
  })();
</script>

<style>
  .gx { padding-block: var(--space-l) var(--space-3xl); }
  .gx__controls {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-2xs);
    max-inline-size: 34rem;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }
  .gx__knobs { display: grid; gap: var(--space-2xs); }
  .gx__knob { display: grid; gap: 0.15rem; }
  .gx__k {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step--2);
    color: var(--ink);
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 0.5em;
  }
  .gx__k b { color: var(--spec-cyan, #4fd6c4); font-weight: 400; }
  .gx__hint { color: var(--ink-dim); font-size: var(--step--2); }
  .gx__knob input[type="range"] {
    inline-size: 100%;
    block-size: 1rem;
    accent-color: var(--spec-cyan, #4fd6c4);
  }
  .gx__actions { display: flex; gap: var(--space-2xs); align-items: center; }
  .gx__go,
  .gx__reset {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step--1);
    padding: 0.4em 0.9em;
    border-radius: var(--radius-s);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--spec-cyan, #4fd6c4) 16%, transparent);
    color: var(--ink);
    cursor: pointer;
  }
  .gx__reset { background: transparent; color: var(--ink-dim); }
  .gx__go[disabled] { opacity: 0.5; cursor: default; }
  .gx__stats {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-s);
    margin-block-start: var(--space-2xs);
  }
  .gx__stats dt {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step--2);
    color: var(--ink-dim);
  }
  .gx__stats dd {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step-0);
    color: var(--spec-cyan, #4fd6c4);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .gx__status {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--step--2);
    color: var(--ink-dim);
    opacity: 0.8;
  }
  .gx__note { margin-block-start: var(--space-2xl); }
  .gx__note h2 { font-size: var(--step-1); margin-block-start: var(--space-l); }
</style>
